Can black holes have Euclidean cores? 
T. Hirayamahirayama@physics.utoronto.ca    and B. Holdombob.holdom@utoronto.ca  

Department of Physics, University of Toronto 

Toronto, Ontario,  M5S1A7, CANADA     
The search for regular black hole solutions in classical gravity leads us to consider a core of Euclidean signature in the interior of a black hole. Solutions of Lorentzian and Euclidean general relativity match in such a way that energy densities and pressures of an isotropic perfect fluid form are everywhere finite and continuous. Although the weak energy condition cannot be satisfied for these solutions in general relativity, it can be when higher derivative terms are added. A numerical study shows how the transition becomes smoother in theories with more derivatives. As an alternative to the Euclidean core, we also discuss a closely related time dependent orbifold construction with a smooth space-like boundary inside the horizon.

Introduction 
The singularity problem of general relativity (GR), as embodied by the Schwarzschild (Schd) solution, may not be a general consequence of a general classical theory of gravity. It may merely be an artifact of truncating a derivative expansion at the lowest term, the Einstein action, and restricting oneself to solutions of that truncated theory. Clearly, before the singularity at  is reached the Einstein action can no longer be trusted. From this viewpoint it is of some interest to see whether the singularity problem that arises in classical gravity could also be resolved within classical gravity. The form of such a resolution in higher derivative theories could also have a bearing on how singularity problems are to be addressed in quantum theories.


We shall refer to some of our results as robust  if they are likely to hold for a general classical theory of gravity with any number of derivatives, with the possible exception of isolated cases in the space of theories. These results have been found to be true for theories with various number of derivatives (checked in theories with 2 and  and often  derivatives), and although we offer no proof, we expect such results to be true quite generally. Any particular theory involving a truncation to some number of derivatives can of course yield spurious and unphysical results (for example the ghosts and tachyons that can appear upon linearization), but the set of robust results applying to the whole set of higher derivative theories should have more significance, and should have some bearing on questions involving strong gravity.


We expect a regular black hole to involve some smooth matter distribution in the interior of the black hole. Interesting regular (nonsingular) solutions must arise from physically acceptable energy-momentum tensors . In the Schd coordinate system the metric of interest is
 
In other attempts to find regular black hole solutions in GR, a constraint on the metric, , is often imposed and  is allowed to have whatever spatial anisotropy is needed to satisfy the equations. But such assumptions are not correct for physical stellar solutions, and so it is questionable that they would apply to regular black holes. We are moving in the opposite direction in this work. In particular we will not constrain  and , and we will take  to have isotropic perfect fluid form. In this framework, both in GR and higher derivative theories, we will see whether various physically motivated energy conditions can be satisfied. Energy conditions play a central role in various no-hair and no-go theorems in GR. See also on the possible violation of the energy conditions.


