A possible multiplicative factor in  arising from a rescaling of  is suppressed. Linear and cubic powers are not allowed. The scalar curvature, for example, at  is . We find that  and  of this form provides an example of a robust solution near the origin. Note that by requiring a regular solution at  we are assuming that the origin actually exists. Thus we do not consider the possibility that a black hole contains a wormhole, a horn or a flux tube. But in section 4 we will discuss a smooth orbifold construction that yields a black hole without a center.


In GR all the parameters in () are determined for given energy density  and pressure  profiles. This is not true for a general  derivative theory, with action
 
In this case the coefficients   and  are free parameters. This freedom is required to match these solutions to the physical large  weak gravity solutions (assuming no singularities in between). This is because the linearized  theory has modes both increasing and decreasing exponentially with large , and the adjustment to zero of the two increasing modes requires two degrees of freedom. This ability to match the small  solutions with the physical large  solutions persists in even higher derivative gravity. For example in a general  derivative theory solutions  near  exist for which four coefficients, , , , , are free parameters.  This freedom is required to adjust to zero the four exponentially growing modes at large .


We remind the reader that the Schd solution itself is not robust since it does not exist in general gravity theories with six or more derivatives. In it was observed that for these theories, () is the only possible solution of the equations when expanded about the origin. This applies when  and  have any power law behavior near , with smooth or vanishing matter distribution up to a possible -function source at .

A crossing point 
The important point is that independent of what the theory is,  for a regular solution. This is a robust result.  But inside the event horizon at ,  is negative, due to the change of signs of  and  at the horizon. Then to match onto a regular solution with  another sign change is required. In other words  must have an even number of sign changes between  and , rather than the single sign  change implied by a single horizon. Thus for a regular black hole with a center  must change sign at some radius  which we refer to as the crossing point , where .


We shall investigate this crossing point by performing a series expansion of the equations of GR and higher derivative theories. Basic properties of this crossing point turn out to be robust. Later we shall use numerical analysis to construct solutions for all  that are compatible with what we know about the origin, the crossing point, and the horizon.


As far as the matter distribution is concerned we shall consider the physically most conservative form for the energy-momentum tensor in the black hole interior: the perfect fluid form with isotropic pressure. Given that  and  have exchanged their space- and time-like roles for the region  we define  and  as follows,
 
This isotropic form would also arise from a general scalar field action with minimal coupling to gravity, given that the scalar field only depends on . But the curvature tensor itself distinguishes between the spatial  direction and the angular directions, and so the isotropic perfect fluid form could be modified through general scalar-gravity coupling terms. But this is not sufficient to justify the use of far from isotropic pressure in regions where the curvature is not large. For definiteness we discuss the case of isotropic pressure everywhere, in which case there are three equations (the ,  and  equations) for the four functions , ,  and . Our basic strategy will be to specify one of these functions and then determine the other three, but this strategy cannot guarantee that both  and  are completely regular. Nor can it guarantee that  and  are physically acceptable and satisfy, for example, the dominant energy condition , or at least the weak energy condition,  and .


