Solutions close to the crossing point 
We find robust regular solutions of type 2 of the following form.
 
There is some number of free parameters depending on the number of derivatives in the theory.  If  is given then  and its derivatives at  are determined.  For GR all the  and  coefficients are determined, for  gravity  and  remain free parameters, for  derivative gravity , , ,  are free, etc. The number of parameters is the same as for the regular solutions at the origin in (), and it the same as the number needed to match onto the Newtonian solution at large .


The existence of these robust solutions is quite remarkable since it implies that all quantities remain finite and are smoothly matched at the boundary between spaces of different signature. In particular the extrinsic curvature vanishes on both sides of the boundary. We emphasize that we are dealing with solutions of different theories, since the  that appears in the action of the theory with Lorentzian signature must be replaced by  in the action of the theory with Euclidean signature. But after accounting for the change of sign of , the field equations are the same in the two theories, and this allows the solutions of the two theories to match.


One might wonder whether there is a single theory that describes both spaces including the crossing point; for example one could consider the theory with . But the theory then becomes nonanalytic in the fields, and if taken seriously, would generate various -function singularities in the field equations at the crossing point. But these singularities are not unique, since different nonanalytic extensions of the theory can give different singularities while keeping the theory on either side the same.(For example if  is the sign function then  up to the existence of singular, ill-defined derivatives at .)  This is related to the controversy in the attempts to define junction conditions at a signature changing boundary (see the last reference of). We are resigned to the fact that the theory is not well defined at the crossing point, and the field equations are ambiguous at this point. We will comment more on this at the end, but for now we will simply define  and  by their approach to the crossing point, using the theories on either side. It is significant then that solutions exist where all physical quantities defined in this way are finite and smooth in the vicinity of the crossing point.


For these solutions (and the more general ones below) we have the following result that is specific to GR.
 
