Orbifolding instead 
As an alternative to signature change, the form of the solution in () suggests a way to remove the Euclidean core region and obtain a regular black hole without a center. A smooth orbifold around  can eliminate the core in the following way. In terms of the proper distance  from the crossing point, the metric can be rewritten as Although the coordinate  covers only  (and ), the metric contains only even powers of , and so we can extend the range of  and impose the orbifold condition at . This gives a smooth space-like boundary at  where curvature invariants are clearly regular and extrinsic curvature vanishes. This would be an illustration of how a smooth time-dependent orbifold ( being time-like) resolves the space-like Schd singularity. Related ideas have been receiving some attention in string theory, especially in regards to the space-like cosmic singularity.


Our results concerning the weak energy condition will also apply to the orbifold construction. There is the additional question of how a gravitational collapse of a smooth matter distribution can change topology to form a black hole without a center. The orbifold possibility lies outside the main development of this paper, but we will return to it briefly in the Discussion. 

More general solutions 
If the solutions in () were the most general possible for a crossing point, then we could proceed to look for completely regular solutions by numerically exploring how the regular solutions at the origin, the crossing point, and the horizon can be joined together. But we find that the solutions in () are not the most general; there are more general solutions that are not completely regular at the crossing point. Fractional powers are involved (and  is the sign function).
 
This contains the terms in () since we can identify , , , etc.(We implicitly replace  by , etc.)  These solutions are robust, and it is these more general solutions that will typically emerge in the numerical analysis. We stress that despite the fractional powers, the curvature invariants (and the extrinsic curvatures) continue to remain finite as the crossing point is approached.(This is more clear if one changes the coordinate from  to the proper distance from the crossing point .) 


General values of the parameters in () can result in discontinuities in physical quantities. We will therefore study a constrained class of solutions that satisfy the following criteria.
 
