When we compare the solutions in GR and  gravity, satisfying the criteria above, we see that in  gravity the leading fractional power in the metric is  rather than . The same is true for , so only in  gravity is  finite and continuous. Similarly  is not continuous in GR, but it is in  gravity. Thus the transition to Euclidean signature has become smoother. In GR we have noticed that the relative size of  and  terms in  and in the curvature invariants are determined by . In  gravity each of the three curvature invariants can depend on a different combination of the same two terms, which depend in more complicated way on the four quantities  and . In  derivative gravity we would expect that solutions satisfying the criteria above have , and thus the curvature invariants would have a leading fractional power of  rather than .


Even though the curvature invariants remain finite as the crossing point is approached, the existence of fractional powers in the metric can imply -function singularities in the curvature invariants. This can be checked independent of the field equations, which we have explained are ambiguous at . The three curvature invariants have -function singularities when  are nonvanishing. These singularities are thus absent in our solution for  gravity. But in this theory a -function singularity would arise in  for example, due to the presence of  and . In  gravity these would also be absent, and so on. 


Thus the basic pattern is that the leading singularities in higher derivative theories occur in higher derivative quantities, and in this way higher derivative theories become more and more smooth. This is the case as long as the higher derivative theory has a solution in which more of the coefficients in () vanish. We must now confirm that such solutions exist, by showing that the solutions we have been describing near  can actually be matched onto solutions that are regular at the origin and the horizon to form a complete black hole solution (the third criteria above). For this we need a numerical treatment. We also need a numerical treatment to check that the weak energy condition can be satisfied in the  theory. And we have already mentioned that it was the numerical study that prompted us to consider seriously the type 2 solutions, due to the difficulty of realizing type 1 solutions.

Numerical study 
For the numerical study the regular solutions at the origin and at the horizon with  provide boundary conditions. But the equations cannot be numerically integrated starting right at the horizon. One strategy is to have the interior matter distribution vanish just before the horizon is reached, so that the Schd solution can be used to supply the initial conditions at a point just inside the horizon. The matter distribution would be continuous but nonsmooth at that point. Alternatively one can use a smooth matter distribution that vanishes at the horizon and has a only a small and high order leading derivative there. Then it can be an arbitrarily good approximation to use the Schd solution to supply the initial condition at a point just inside the horizon. There is a similar numerical problem with integrating from  in  gravity. Here we use the series solution in () to provide initial conditions at a small but finite value of . The solution then depends on the free parameters in this expansion, of which there are two in  gravity.


For GR there are no undetermined parameters in the boundary conditions, once  is given. In fact one of the equations can be solved analytically for  given , and the constraints on  can be satisfied even before  is found. The numerical results for  then confirms what we have already alluded to for GR:  are in general nonzero. This eliminates the possibility of having the completely regular solutions in () in GR, at least for the form of  we are considering.


